title: For Sale/Trade:  Saiga 12 Bullpup
postcontent:
Saiga 12 Bullpup with two magazines.  1 5rd and 1 10rd mag.  This has been a good gun but I am just not much of a shotgun guy.  I traded for it.  Shot it.  Took some boy scouts out to shoot it.  We all had a blast shooting targets with birdshot and buckshot.  But...  Then it just sat in the safe.  

I am a Semi Auto rifle kinda guy.  I like AR-15s.  Especially in 6.5 Grendel, 300BLK, or other rounds.  I have two solid 5.56 uppers so, not really feeling the need for anymore of those.  I like pistol caliber carbines.  9mm, 40sw, 45acp.  Whatever.  9mm is cheapest to shoot, but I have a lot of 40sw in my house so...

I like 308 semi autos.  I really would like a good FNAR, or AR10.  The new GenII DPMS seem interesting.  If its a 3moa shooter, I am not interested.  If its a 1 moa or better shooter, I am likely interested.  I reload, so if your 308 semi auto bruises the brass, I will pass.

I dont have an AK, but am interested in them.  Arsenal, Saiga, Vepr, these things interest me.  7.62x39 or 54r.  AK74...

I like bolt action rifles in long range, but not shoulder punishing calibers.  So 6.5 lapua/creedmore/260.  I currently do not have a 308 bolt so for the right now, sure.  I like precision when it comes to rifles, so if you cannot show .6moa or better 5 round groups for your bolt, then I am probably not interested.

Optics.  I like optics.  Higher end optics.  HD optics.  Or a decent night vision/thermal.  Red dots...  Probably not.  I have found that the primary arms red dots do everything I could ever ask for and just make me smile.  Trijicon 4x or 6x, or accupoint variable power are nice.  Higher end Vortex, Zeiss, Burris, Bushnell all intrigue me.  Laser range finding scopes... nah.  I already own one and it does all I need in that category.

I value this russian made saiga at around $1250.  So keep that in mind when discussing trades.

Butt and Forestock are checkered, this is the "Deluxe Border" model in .38/.357 Magnum and the 20" octagon barrel with adjustable front and rear sights and case hardening.
Winchester’s1873 rifle was the “Rifle that Won the West.” It is chambered in the economical .38/.357 Magnum cartridge. A cowboy could have both a lever-action rifle and his six shooter, and needed only one cartridge belt for both. Most Texas Rangers and every old West cowboy worth his salt carried 1873 rifles. Chappo, the son of Apache war chief Geronimo, packed an 1873. And Buffalo Bill carried an 1873 lever-action rifle along with a pair of .44-40 Colts in 1876 when he worked as an Army scout. This piece of rifle history is available in a variety of distinctive models including this Special Cimarron branded Deluxe Short rifle. Don't let that fool you though, it has a 10+1 capacity and power to spare.

title: For Sale/Trade:  AK-47 on US made receiver
postcontent: Romanian Guard G pattern AKM, also know as an AK-47.  The "donor" kit was manufactured in 1980.  The US made an compliant receiver is manufactured by NoDak Spud, in Minnesota.  This rifle was designed from the factory as a semi-automatic weapon, as was issued to the Romanian Guard, a rough equivalent of the National or Home Guard which was active during the Cold War.  This example has a chrome lined barrel, a muzzle brake, and the cleaning rod, but no bayonet lug.  The furniture seems to be typical Soviet pattern laminate wood stock and forearm with a USA made polymer grip.  The buttstock has the integral cleaning kit and sports the common AK sling. Wood and metal is in a 90% or better condition, similar to all pattern 3 stamped receiver AKs.  Selling with on Bulgarian polymer magazine.

postcontent:
Taser X3 promotional videos:
•	https://youtu.be/n0PWcjDpTvE

•	https://youtu.be/U53B-g-73yY

Taser X3 manufacturer’s support:
•	https://www.taser.com/support/products/taser-x3


Taser X3 Description:

The TASER X3 ECD is a software upgradable, 3-shot ECD manufactured by TASER International, Inc. ECDs use propelled wires or direct contact to conduct energy to affect the sensory and motor functions of the nervous system. The X3 ECD offers a multi-shot capability that previous-generation TASER ECDs do not. The X3 ECD deploys Smart Cartridges one at a time. It is possible to apply energy beyond the initial burst to a deployed cartridge without deploying the remaining cartridges. It also is possible to apply a Warning ArcTM display or drive-stun without deploying any of the cartridges loaded in the ECD.

The X3 ECD uses three replaceable X3 Smart Cartridges containing compressed nitrogen to deploy two small probes that are attached to the X3 ECD by insulated conductive wires. The X3 ECD transmits electrical pulses along the wires and into the body affecting the sensory and motor functions of the peripheral nervous system. The energy can penetrate up to 1.5 cumulative inches of clothing, or 0.75 inches per probe. The cartridges are available with various wire lengths from 15’ to 35’ (4.6 meters to 10.7 meters). X3 Smart Cartridges are equipped with Charge DiffusionTM probes for optimal Neuro Muscular Incapacitation (NMI) pulse delivery.

The X3 ECD’s Trilogy LogTM can be uploaded securely to EVIDENCE.COM, where the information is encrypted, stored securely, and organized into dashboards that allow your agency to easily monitor the usage and system status of your entire arsenal of X3 ECDs.
The X3 ECD’s optional TACOMTM Digital Power Magazine, or TPM, enables the X3 ECD to communicate wirelessly to other TACOM enabled ECDs such as the AXON Tactical Computer for time synchronization and event triggering. Furthermore, the X3 ECD features a Power Optimization Control (POC) capability that continually monitors the power remaining in the battery pack and, when needed, shuts down peripheral functions to maintain critical NMI capability while warning the user when the battery power reaches low levels.

The X3 ECD has an internal memory that stores the operating software and a record of every deployment. See the "Trilogy Log" section in this manual for more details.

The X3 ECD’s capabilities are encased within a rugged unibody chassis. This rugged structure protects the enclosed circuitry from hostile environments. Additionally, the unibody polymer frame provides much greater structural integrity and impact survivability than previous clamshell housings.

Price: [strike]$600[/strike] $500 - Rifle w/A2 Stock, 2 40rd ProMags, Original Flash Hider, Bayonet w/sheath & carry handle. If you would like any of the extra items listed below I can give you a price break depending on what you want with it.

Century Arm C93 Sporter, 5.56, 16.25” 1:9 twist barrel, fluted chamber, roller lock bolt system, black synthetic A2 stock and forend (with heatshield). 

I’ve owned a number of Century rifles (some of the crap ones that never fired or cycled correctly and some of the CETME’s that were top notch) and I can say this is by far the most reliable one I’ve ever shot. Picked this up a few months ago as a project rifle for long range but it’s just not my cup of tea. I love the look, and it’s a lot more reliable than I imagined when I bought it, but it’s just too bulky for my taste and I want something with a bit more range. One thing I was impressed with was its accuracy - after sighting it in I was hitting roughly 3” groups at 100 yards – so someone who actually knows how to shoot can easily hit 2” or smaller groups.

I purchased this used and the main reason being that it looked to have been a shooter, which meant it functioned, and I wanted something can throw steel cased ammo through easily. I disassembled and checked every part of the gun, cleaned it and lubed it to death (as these things love oil baths). First trip to the range I put 100rds of Tula 223, 100rds M855, 100rds AE 556, 100rds of AE 223 and 40rds of Wolf 223 without a hitch. Functioned flawlessly with all the ammo I used and all 4 of the mags. The only time I had an issue was when I was shooting with a suppressor the last round in each of the promags caused an FTF which I can only attribute to the increased back pressure from the suppressor and/or possibly weaker spring in the promags vs the original HK mag. So 2 FTF’s out of probably 1000 rounds is extremely good for an HK clone built by CAI (if you know their history).
